Add the definition of regular sequences and induction principles for them.

Despite the branch name this PR does not define depth. I would appreciate any suggestions on how to shorten the names of lemmas in this PR, because they feel unreasonably long. ~~The name `Module.Submodule.complementedLattice` was changed to `Submodule.complementedLattice` because as far as I can't tell this is the only instance of the namespace `Module.Submodule`, and having that namespace breaks `open Submodule` while within the `Module` namespace. I can extract this change into another PR if necessary.~~ (This change has been merged.)

```suggestion
Properties of regular sequences encode information about singularities of a
```

Can/should this be a module docstring? If not, please drop the `!` on the first line of this suggestion.
```suggestion
/-!
In theory, regularity of `rs : List ` on `M` makes sense as soon as
`[Monoid ]`, `[AddCommGroup M]`, and `[DistribMulAction  M]`.
Instead of `Ideal.ofList (rs.take i)  ( : Submodule R M)` we use
` (j : Fin i), rs[j]  ( : AddSubgroup M)`.
However it's not clear that this is a useful generalization.
If we add the assumption `[SMulCommClass   M]` this is essentially the
same as focusing on the commutative ring case, passing to the monoid ring
`[abelianization of ]`.
-/
```

Hmm, not sure it makes sense as a module docstring. I wanted to include it as a warning/suggestion(?) to future maintainers of this code, explaining why I defined it like this and not in another plausible way. I don't think it's useful for a client looking at the documentation to see it. I've changed to a multi-line comment though
I think that all these names that start with `isWeaklyRegular` can just be in the parent namespace. Otherwise the fully-qualified names become really long, and have redundancy.

Fwiw the fully qualified names are already super long, since they live in the namespace `RingTheory.Sequence` (I chose this namespace because `Sequence` is too ambiguous on its own). When writing this I was thinking a client could just open `IsWeaklyRegular`, but the redundancy is kinda silly. I would've defaulted to naming things like this `IsWeaklyRegular.cons_iff` but the `@[mk_iff]` naming scheme made me think this was preferred. I'll move stuff out of the `IsWeaklyRegular`/`IsRegular` namespaces as appropriate.

Also, is `RingTheory.Sequence.IsRegular` an okay name if we already have the global name `IsRegular`? I would prefer to put `Sequence` in the namespace rather than the name, but maybe it should be renamed to `IsRegularSequence` and `IsWeaklyRegular` renamed to `IsWeaklyRegularSequence` (both in the global namespace)? This seems like an annoyingly long name though
And it is not uncommon for mathlib to use `W` for weak/weakly (e.g. `WSeq`, `WCovBy`) so maybe `IsWRegularSeq` is also good? (less sure about this one)
Another choice is to have `List.IsRegular` so you can write `rs.IsRegular M`.

I initially wanted to have something like `abbrev RingTheory.Sequence R := List R` and define `Sequence.IsRegular`, but for some reason it was causing me problems. It seemed like a bad idea to introduce a superfluous abbreviaton for lists just because mathematicians call lists sequences, so I settled on putting it in the namespace

I think also `IsRegular` is way too generic to put in the list namespace. The existing global `IsRegular` should probably be in a namespace too, imo. Why should "regular" unqualified mean this and not regularity of a sequence, of a Noetherian ring, of a noncommutative ring (vonn neumann regularity), or any of the million other predicates that mathematicians call regular?

I am happy with the current choice of names. But I also like the `Is(W)RegularSeq` suggestion. I'll leave it up to you.

bors d+

I think at the moment I'm going to keep it as is but will keep an eye on it going forward. It's possible that we'll quickly run into headaches where we want to talk about both kinds of `IsRegular` eg when talking about the depth of a ring
